Day 4: Forms in React

Forms are used to collect user input such as:

Name
Email
Mobile Number
Password

Examples:

Login Form
Registration Form
Contact Form
What is a Controlled Component?

A Controlled Component is a form element whose value is controlled by React state.

Instead of letting the browser manage the input value, React manages it using useState.

Example 1: Single Input Field
import { useState } from 'react';

function UserForm() {

    const [name, setName] = useState('');

    return (
        <div>
            <input
                type="text"
                placeholder="Enter Name"
                value={name}
                onChange={(e) => setName(e.target.value)}
            />

            <h3>Name: {name}</h3>
        </div>
    );
}

export default UserForm;
How it works

When user types:

Priyadharshini

onChange gets triggered:

onChange={(e) => setName(e.target.value)}

and updates state.

React automatically updates:

Name: Priyadharshini
Understanding onChange
onChange={(e) => setName(e.target.value)}

Where:

e.target.value

contains the current value typed by the user.

Example:

Input Box : Priya

then:

e.target.value = "Priya"
Example 2: Login Form
import { useState } from 'react';

function LoginForm() {

    const [username, setUsername] = useState('');
    const [password, setPassword] = useState('');

    return (
        <div>

            <input
                type="text"
                placeholder="Username"
                value={username}
                onChange={(e) => setUsername(e.target.value)}
            />

            <br /><br />

            <input
                type="password"
                placeholder="Password"
                value={password}
                onChange={(e) => setPassword(e.target.value)}
            />

            <h3>Username: {username}</h3>
            <h3>Password: {password}</h3>

        </div>
    );
}

export default LoginForm;
Handling Form Submission
const handleSubmit = (e) => {

    e.preventDefault();

    console.log(username);
    console.log(password);
};

Why use:

e.preventDefault();

Because it prevents the page from refreshing when the form is submitted.

Complete Example
import { useState } from 'react';

function LoginForm() {

    const [username, setUsername] = useState('');
    const [password, setPassword] = useState('');

    const handleSubmit = (e) => {

        e.preventDefault();

        alert(
            `Username: ${username}
Password: ${password}`
        );
    };

    return (

        <form onSubmit={handleSubmit}>

            <input
                type="text"
                placeholder="Username"
                value={username}
                onChange={(e) => setUsername(e.target.value)}
            />

            <br /><br />

            <input
                type="password"
                placeholder="Password"
                value={password}
                onChange={(e) => setPassword(e.target.value)}
            />

            <br /><br />

            <button type="submit">
                Login
            </button>

        </form>
    );
}

export default LoginForm;


Multiple Fields Using One State Object
const [user, setUser] = useState({
    name: '',
    email: ''
});

Update field:

onChange={(e) =>
    setUser({
        ...user,
        name: e.target.value
    })
}

The ...user keeps existing values intact.

Interview Questions
What is a Controlled Component?

A form element whose value is controlled by React state.

Why use Controlled Components?
Easy validation
Easy form submission
Single source of truth
Better control over user input
What is e.target.value?

It returns the current value entered by the user in an input field.

Why use preventDefault()?

To prevent the browser's default form submission behavior (page refresh).
